00:49:43.400 --> 00:49:47.633
but if I'm not in love with at least
somebody in those 50 pages,

00:49:47.633 --> 00:49:48.900
I'll stop.

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:52.600
At some point in the last 10 years,
I just-- life is too short,

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:55.033
I'm not reading it if it
doesn't really grab me.

00:49:55.033 --> 00:49:58.233
And that's including
some of the greats,

00:49:58.233 --> 00:49:59.800
contemporary great writers.

00:49:59.800 --> 00:50:01.900
It's just like I don't
like this writing,

00:50:01.900 --> 00:50:03.133
I don't like the style of it,

00:50:03.133 --> 00:50:07.767
and people who are very hot
aren't necessarily people who...

00:50:07.767 --> 00:50:08.400
But that's okay.

00:50:08.400 --> 00:50:11.734
I mean there should be lots of flavors
and lots of different styles.

00:50:11.734 --> 00:50:14.667
But I stop after awhile.

00:50:14.667 --> 00:50:16.033
male: What about non-fiction?

00:50:16.033 --> 00:50:17.867
Anita: I like them, I read them.

00:50:17.867 --> 00:50:21.100
male: But they're not necessarily
characters that you can like or not.

00:50:21.100 --> 00:50:25.033
Anita: Oh, no, well if it's well written
and it's compelling,

00:50:25.033 --> 00:50:26.467
I really enjoy non-fiction.

00:50:26.467 --> 00:50:30.433
I'm reading a fair amount of history
again in preparation for this book

00:50:30.433 --> 00:50:31.533
that I'm hoping to write.

00:50:31.533 --> 00:50:34.633
And I enjoy that too.

00:50:34.633 --> 00:50:41.834
So, last summer I loved the Julia Child
biography by her nephew.

00:50:41.834 --> 00:50:43.333
If you saw 'Julie and Julia',
you should really read the book,

00:50:43.333 --> 00:50:44.967
it's really fun.

00:50:44.967 --> 00:50:46.533
Really nice writing, really non-fiction.

00:50:46.533 --> 00:50:48.467
And I got to meet Julia Child
and talk to her,

00:50:48.467 --> 00:50:52.800
so I could hear her voice when
she lived here many years ago.

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:57.200
So that was fun.

00:50:57.200 --> 00:50:59.300
It was my last really fun non-fiction book.

00:50:59.300 --> 00:51:04.900
The rest has been history,
but interesting.

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:05.600
So that's what I'm reading.

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:07.300
I'm up to here with
American history right now,

00:51:07.300 --> 00:51:14.000
so that's why it's hard for me to reach out
for the novels that don't [inaudible].

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.767
male: You went in one of these camps,
and so what happens to you internally.

00:51:16.767 --> 00:51:20.266
It seems like there were people
popping up on the shore all the time.

00:51:20.266 --> 00:51:21.667
200 people in this camp.

00:51:21.667 --> 00:51:26.700
It's going to be way too full,
in a day, a week, a month,

00:51:26.700 --> 00:51:28.834
so they gotta do something.

00:51:28.834 --> 00:51:32.567
They can't take them out,
the boat's gone.

00:51:32.567 --> 00:51:33.600
Anita: Well what happens.

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:35.233
male: They essentially let them go.
Anita: They let them go.

00:51:35.233 --> 00:51:36.200
male: They all tell the same story basically.

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:37.967
Anita: They do let them go,
for the most part in Atlit.

00:51:37.967 --> 00:51:40.633
But what happened is
so many people started coming,

00:51:40.633 --> 00:51:43.266
they built an enormous camp in Cyprus.

00:51:43.266 --> 00:51:47.767
So that's if you saw the movie 'Exodus',
or read that book.

00:51:47.767 --> 00:51:51.333
That's not a great book by the way,
a terrible book. [laughter]

00:51:51.333 --> 00:51:56.133
Anita: It's a better movie than a book.
They took the dramatic part of it.

00:51:56.133 --> 00:52:00.200
They built this enormous
internment camp in Cyprus.

00:52:00.200 --> 00:52:02.266
And people were there for years.

00:52:02.266 --> 00:52:07.500
And it was hot and miserable, and also,
for all of that there were millions,

00:52:07.500 --> 00:52:11.533
there were many many marriages,
there were many children born.

00:52:11.533 --> 00:52:13.700
People taught school to the children,

00:52:13.700 --> 00:52:15.100
they taught music to the children.

00:52:15.100 --> 00:52:20.667
So, they made life happen
in this incredibly hot miserable place.

00:52:20.667 --> 00:52:23.500
So that's what happened to a lot of them.

00:52:23.500 --> 00:52:25.934
I mean it was at relatively
[Inaudible] this whole coast line.

00:52:25.934 --> 00:52:27.800
So a lot of people did get in and...

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:29.800
male: Yeah, like maybe catch one
in three or something.

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:31.600
Anita: Right, so the people
who were in camp.

00:52:31.600 --> 00:52:34.667
And at least some of them
actually wound up having family,

00:52:34.667 --> 00:52:36.333
so they got released to family.

00:52:36.333 --> 00:52:38.734
If they were sick,
they got sent to hospitals.

00:52:38.734 --> 00:52:42.433
Children in particular if they were orphans
would get sent to orphanages.

00:52:42.433 --> 00:52:46.500
So the British were a real mixed bag
as occupiers.

00:52:46.500 --> 00:52:49.066
They were both compassionate and jerks.

00:52:49.066 --> 00:52:51.967
I mean, and it depended on the individual
as much as anything else.

00:52:51.967 --> 00:52:56.033
But, they were-- I remember Barak
who gave this tour talking and saying,

00:52:56.033 --> 00:52:59.800
"You gotta have, if your prison camp is gonna
be run by anybody, you want the British,

00:52:59.800 --> 00:53:02.800
because they believe in rules."

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:03.967
male: So did the Germans?
Anita: Huh?

00:53:03.967 --> 00:53:05.000
male: So did the Germans.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:06.100
Anita: Well, in a different--

00:53:06.100 --> 00:53:08.033
but they also believed
in the Geneva conventions

00:53:08.033 --> 00:53:10.734
and that these were not prisoners,
these were in fact internees.

00:53:10.734 --> 00:53:12.333
And they knew that they were.

00:53:12.333 --> 00:53:16.300
And they were-- and there was a lot of guilt
among some of the British as well.

00:53:16.300 --> 00:53:19.433
They were not all happy
about being put in this position.

00:53:19.433 --> 00:53:23.734
There were anti-Semites who were very happy
about being put in this position.

00:53:23.734 --> 00:53:30.367
So they were, they were just human beings
in ultimately an impossible situation.

00:53:30.367 --> 00:53:32.934
As it still is to this very day.

00:53:32.934 --> 00:53:35.467
male: So this seems like actually
the British had a fig leaf

00:53:35.467 --> 00:53:38.900
and they made some treaty or something
and promised that they would stop immigration.

00:53:38.900 --> 00:53:39.967
Anita: Right.
male: Clearly they can't.

00:53:39.967 --> 00:53:40.600
Anita: They can't exactly.

00:53:40.600 --> 00:53:42.700
male: And clearly they can't shoot them
at the water's edge,

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:44.000
or they're not prepared to.

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:44.700
Anita: They're not prepared to.

00:53:44.700 --> 00:53:48.633
And at the same time they had to
keep the Arab population at the same saying,

00:53:48.633 --> 00:53:51.166
"We are, we are enforcing these quotas."

00:53:51.166 --> 00:53:54.333
male: They're making some show
of doing their best.

00:53:54.333 --> 00:53:57.400
Anita: Right.
And they did their...

00:53:57.400 --> 00:54:01.266
And then they opened Cyprus
which really was this big holding camp

00:54:01.266 --> 00:54:03.000
which became an international embarrassment.

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:08.533
Because people got sick there
and people would die there, it was.

00:54:08.533 --> 00:54:10.133
male: So many people in squalor.

00:54:10.133 --> 00:54:11.266
Anita: Yes, too many people.

00:54:11.266 --> 00:54:12.367
male: And you can't park them there forever.

00:54:12.367 --> 00:54:14.133
Anita: Right, exactly. But they were there--
it felt like forever.

00:54:14.133 --> 00:54:15.633
They were there for years.

00:54:15.633 --> 00:54:18.233
In Atlit, people were there
for weeks or months.

00:54:18.233 --> 00:54:20.567
In Cyprus they were stuck for a long time.

00:54:20.567 --> 00:54:23.867
And it was an island,
it was hard to escape.

00:54:23.867 --> 00:54:25.300
male: Whenever I think about it,

00:54:25.300 --> 00:54:27.734
it just reminds me of
our own southern border.

00:54:27.734 --> 00:54:30.967
There are people trying sneak
across in the dark of night.

00:54:30.967 --> 00:54:32.266
Hope of a better life.

00:54:32.266 --> 00:54:34.433
A community up here
if they can make it,

00:54:34.433 --> 00:54:36.266
that they can thread right into.

00:54:36.266 --> 00:54:38.400
And I mean some fraction they catch.

00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:42.367
Of course we're not shooting them
at the water's edge either.

00:54:42.367 --> 00:54:43.233
Anita: We're not shooting them.

00:54:43.233 --> 00:54:47.333
male: But neither do we make it pleasant
enough that they are excited about.

00:54:47.333 --> 00:54:52.367
I suspect actually that 9 out of
10 make it clean and clear over time.

00:54:52.367 --> 00:54:55.633
Anita: Probably. Fewer now
because the economy is so bad.

00:54:55.633 --> 00:54:58.567
But yeah, I think this is sort of
an international classic story

00:54:58.567 --> 00:55:04.467
about trying to get into a place that you're
sort of not legally supposed to be part of.

00:55:04.467 --> 00:55:07.767
And the world is more porous
than it's ever been before.

00:55:07.767 --> 00:55:10.166
Or at borders anyway.

00:55:10.166 --> 00:55:13.400
No matter what we try.

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:14.800
female: We're just about out of time.

00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:16.967
Thank you so much for coming,
this is wonderful.

00:55:16.967 --> 00:55:17.767
Anita: Thank You.

00:55:17.767 --> 00:55:22.033
[applause]

